# Debuggable Returns

Never `return` a function/method call directly. Always capture the result into a named variable on its own line, then `return` that variable. This lets a debugger stop on the `return` line with the value already inspectable.

Applies to all `return` statements: async (`return await fn(...)`), sync (`return fn(...)`), method chains (`return foo.bar().baz()`), built-in coercions (`return Number(x) > 0`), and `.map()`/`.filter()` callbacks.

## Examples

```typescript
async findById(id: string): Promise<Row | null> {
  return await getDb().selectFrom("t").selectAll().where("id", "=", id).executeTakeFirst();
}

async delete(id: string): Promise<boolean> {
  const result = await getDb().deleteFrom("t").where("id", "=", id).executeTakeFirst();
  return Number(result.numDeletedRows) > 0;
}

items.map((item) => {
  return buildDetail(item);
});
```

```typescript
async findById(id: string): Promise<Row | null> {
  const row = await getDb().selectFrom("t").selectAll().where("id", "=", id).executeTakeFirst();
  return row ?? null;
}

async delete(id: string): Promise<boolean> {
  const result = await getDb().deleteFrom("t").where("id", "=", id).executeTakeFirst();
  const deletedCount = Number(result.numDeletedRows);
  return deletedCount > 0;
}

items.map((item) => {
  const detail = buildDetail(item);
  return detail;
});
```

## Allowed Exceptions

- Early returns of literals / simple expressions: `return null;`, `return [];`, `return row ?? null;`, `return deletedCount > 0;` — these don't invoke a function, so a breakpoint on the line already shows everything.
- Arrow-function shorthand with no body (`(x) => x * 2`) — there's no `return` statement to break on.
